{"title_page": "Grammatical gender in German", "text_new": "{{German grammar}}\n'''Grammatical gender in German''' refers to the division of [[German nouns]] into three [[Grammatical gender|grammatical genders]]. All [[German language|German]] nouns are included in one of three genders: masculine, feminine or neuter. However the gender is not relevant to the plural forms of nouns.{{Sfn|Donaldson|2007|pp=33\u201337}}{{Sfn|Durrell|2017|pp=1\u20135}}\n\nIn German, it is useful to memorize nouns with their accompanying [[German articles#Definite article|definite article]] in order to remember their gender.<ref group=\"note\">While Donaldson (2007) says that it is imperative to do so, Durrell (2017) only mentions that is an ideal method.</ref> However, for about 80% of nouns, the grammatical gender can be deduced from their singular and plural forms{{Fix|text=does this mean the nominative forms?}} and their meaning.{{Sfn|Donaldson|2007|pp=33\u201337}}{{Sfn|Durrell|2017|pp=1\u20135}}\n\n== Noun forms ==\n[[Morphological derivation|Derivational]] suffixes in particular, together with most noun endings, consistently relate with specific genders, and there are very few frequent exceptions to this (as reflected in the first column). Nevertheless, the details in the second column are not solid rules, and their irregularities should be noted.{{Sfn|Durrell|2017|pp=1\u20135}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Noun forms and gender{{Sfn|Donaldson|2007|pp=33\u201337}}{{Sfn|Durrell|2017|pp=1\u20135}}<ref group=\"note\" name=\":1\">The lists of exceptions here do not necessarily include all of them. Furthermore, the notes referring to the information in the chart are referenced using the pages on its caption.</ref>\n!Masculine endings{{refn|group=Nf|Except ''das Genus'' (gender), ''das Korpus'' (collection of texts), ''das Labor'' (laboratory), ''das Tempus'' (tense), ''das Virus'' (virus).}}\n!Masculine gender indications\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" |''-ant, -ast, -ich, -ig, -ismus, -ling, -or, -us''\n|The majority of nouns which come from [[Germanic strong verb|strong verbs]] without a [[suffix]] (but often with a vowel change).{{refn|group=Nf|But: ''das Grab'', ''das Lied'', ''das Ma\u00df'', ''das Schloss'', ''das Verbot''.}}\n|-\n|60% of nouns in -''el'' and ''-er'', as well as 80% of those in ''-en'',{{refn|group=Nf|Since no feminine nouns end in ''en''.}} are masculine.{{refn|group=Nf|Nouns with ''-er'' arising from verbs are masculine (anyhow, most of them describe male human beings). Four categories which are not masculine:\n* Nouns which stem from verb infinitives in ''-en'' are neuter (''das Kochen'');\n* Nouns in ''-sel'' and ''-tel'' are neuter (see the first column);\n* Roughly 15% of the other nouns in ''-el'', ''-en'' and ''-er'' are neuter;\n* Circa 25% of those in ''-el'' and ''-er'' are feminine.}}\n|-\n|67% of [[Syllable|monosyllabic]] nouns.{{refn|group=Nf|The rest are 19% neuter and 14% feminine.}}\n|-\n!Feminine endings{{refn|group=Nf|Apart from ''das Sofa'', ''das Genie'', ''der Atlantik'', ''der Pazifik'', ''das Mosiak'', ''das Abitur'', ''das Futur'', ''das Purpur''.}}\n!Feminine gender indications\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |''-a, -anz, -ei, -enz, -heit,'' ''-ie,''<ref group=\"note\" name=\":0\">Donaldson (2007) asserts that all nouns of French origin ending in ''-ie'', ''-ik'' and ''-ion'' are feminine.</ref> ''-ik,''<ref group=\"note\" name=\":0\" /> ''-in,''{{refn|group=Nf|Chemical terms which end in ''-in'' (pronounced [[Help:IPA/Standard German|[i\u02d0n]]]) are neuter (''das Benzin'', ''das Protein'').}} ''-keit,''\n''-schaft, -sion,''<ref group=\"note\" name=\":0\" /> ''-t\u00e4t, -tion,''<ref group=\"note\" name=\":0\" /> ''-ung,'' ''-ur''\n|Most nouns ending in ''-t'' originating from verbs.{{refn|group=Nf|Except for: ''der Dienst'', ''der Durst'', ''der Frost'', ''der Verdienst'', ''der Verlust'', ''das Gift''.}}\n|-\n|90% of nouns in ''-e''.{{refn|group=Nf|The main exceptions are:\n* A few neuter nouns, the most common of which are: ''das Auge'', ''das Ende'', ''das Erbe'' (when it means \u2018inheritance\u2019 or \u2018heritage\u2019), ''das Finale'', ''das Image'', ''das Interesse'', ''das Prestige'', ''das Regime''.\n* ''der Charme'' and ''der K\u00e4se'';\n* Most nouns with the prefix ''Ge-'' are neuter, even if they end with an ''-e'' (see the chart);\n* Nine exceptional masculines: ''der Buchstabe'', ''der Friede'', ''der Funke'', ''der Gedanke'', ''der Glaube'', ''der Haufe'', ''der Name'', ''der Same'', ''der Wille'' (these end in ''-n'' in the plural and in the [[accusative]] and [[dative]] singular, but in ''-ns'' in the [[genitive]] singular{{refn|[[#Durrell2017|Durrell 2017]], p. 35}});\n* The weak masculines which are names of male persons and animals: ''der Affe'', ''der Bote'', ''der Junge'', ''der L\u00f6we'' (the weak masculines are a group of nouns, most of which denote male humans or animals, which end in ''-n'' or ''-en'' in the plural and in all cases besides the [[nominative]]{{refn|[[#Durrell2017|Durrell 2017]], p. 33}}).}}\n|-\n!Neuter endings{{refn|group=Nf|Excluding ''die Firma'', ''der Streusel'', ''der Irrtum'', ''der Reichtum'', ''der Konsum''.}}\n!Neuter gender indications\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" |''-chen,'' ''-lein,'' ''-ma, -ment, -sel, -tel, -tum, -um''\n|90% of the nouns with the [[prefix]] ''Ge-''.{{refn|group=Nf|The irregularities here are: \n* Categories of humans (''der Gehilfe''\u2013''die Gehilfin'' \u2018assistant\u2019 etc);\n* A large number of feminine and masculine nouns:\n** ''die Geb\u00e4rde'', ''die Geb\u00fchr'', ''die Geburt'', ''die Geduld'', ''die Gefahr'', ''die Gemeinde'', ''die Geschichte'', ''die Geschwulst'', ''die Gestalt'', ''die Gew\u00e4hr'', ''die Gewalt'';\n** ''der Gebrauch'', ''der Gedanke'', ''der Gefallen'' (favour), ''der Gehalt'' (content), ''der Gehorsam'', ''der Genuss'', ''der Geruch'', ''der Gesang'', ''der Geschmack'', ''der Gestank'', ''der Gewinn'' (''Gefallen'' and ''Gehalt'' are neuter when they mean \u2018pleasure\u2019 and \u2018salary\u2019, respectively.).}}\n|-\n|Two-thirds of nouns in ''-nis'' and ''-sal''.{{refn|group=Nf|About a third of them are feminine. More specifically, nouns derived from adjectives with the suffix ''-nis'' are primarily feminine.}}\n|-\n|Most nouns ending in ''-al'', ''-an'', ''-ar'', ''-\u00e4r'', ''-at'', ''-ent'', ''-ett'', ''-ier'', ''-iv'', ''-o'' and ''-on'' (which are of foreign origin), provided that they designate things.{{refn|group=Nf|If they describe persons, they are masculine. Irregularities: ''der Altar'', ''der Apparat'', ''der Automat'', ''der Kanal'', ''der Kanton'', ''der Kommentar'', ''die Manier'', ''die Moral'', ''die Person'', ''der Salat'', ''der Senat'', ''der Skandal''.}} \n|}\n'''Notes: exceptions and irregularities'''{{reflist|group=Nf}}\n\n== Noun meanings ==\nThe gender of many nouns can be seen by their meaning. However, in almost all circumstances, the rules in the paragraph above override those given here.{{Sfn|Donaldson|2007|pp=33\u201337}}{{Sfn|Durrell|2017|pp=6\u20139|p=}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Noun meanings and gender{{Sfn|Donaldson|2007|pp=33\u201337}}{{Sfn|Durrell|2017|pp=6\u20139|p=}}<ref group=\"note\" name=\":1\"/>\n! rowspan=\"10\" |Masculine\n|width=450pt|Male human beings and animals.\n|-\n|Seasons, months and days of the week.{{Refn|As usual, compounds carry the gender of their second component.|group=B}}\n|-\n|Compass points, words about winds and types of weather.\n|-\n|Rocks and minerals. \n|-\n|Alcoholic and plant-based drinks.\n|-\n|Car brands.\n|-\n|Rivers outside Germany.{{Refn|The nouns who end in either -''a'' or -''e'' are typically feminine.|group=B}}\n|-\n|Names of currencies.\n|-\n|Mountains and mountain ranges.\n|-\n|Rain and Precipitation <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deutsch.lingolia.com/en/grammar/nouns-and-articles/gender|title=der, die, das \u2013 Gender of Nouns in German Grammar|website=deutsch.lingolia.com|language=en|access-date=2019-12-10}}</ref>\n|-\n! rowspan=\"6\" |Feminine\n|Female animals and humans.\n|-\n|Planes, ships and motorbikes.{{Refn|Names of planes and ships frequently have the gender of their base words.|group=B}}\n|-\n|Names of numerals.\n|-\n| -schaft ending words <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://study.com/academy/lesson/german-nouns-masculine-feminine-neuter.html|title=German Nouns: Masculine, Feminine, Neuter|website=Study.com|language=en|access-date=2019-12-10}}</ref>\n|-\n|Music as a noun<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://study.com/academy/lesson/german-nouns-masculine-feminine-neuter.html|title=German Nouns: Masculine, Feminine, Neuter|website=Study.com|language=en|access-date=2019-12-10}}</ref>\n|-\n| -t\u00e4t ending nouns <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://resources.german.lsa.umich.edu/grammatik/gender/|title=Predicting Noun Genders - Deutsch 101-326|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-10}}</ref>\n|-\n! rowspan=\"8\" |Neuter\n|Young human beings and animals.\n|-\n|Metals and chemical elements.\n|-\n|Scientific units.\n|-\n|Letters and musical notes.{{Refn|Letters are masculine in Swiss German.|group=B}}\n|-\n|Different parts of speech used as nouns (most importantly, this category contains verb infinitives, but also languages, colours and so on).\n|-\n|Caf\u00e9s, cinemas, hotels and restaurants.\n|-\n|Names of companies with no article.{{Refn|Less commonly, these names act as feminines.|group=B}}\n|-\n|Cities, towns, countries, provinces and continents.{{Refn|Except several feminines, masculines and names ending in -''a'', -''e'', -''ei'' or -''ie'' (besides ''Afrika'' and ''China'').|group=B}}\n|}\n'''Notes for the chart:'''{{reflist|group=B}}\n\n== Special cases ==\nThe genders of a few nouns are not fixed, and may be linked to regional or register differences. There are a number of words with two meanings distinguished by gender.{{Sfn|Donaldson|2007|pp=33\u201337}}{{Sfn|Durrell|2017|p=|pp=12\u201316}}\n\n=== Compounds and abbreviations ===\nCompound words usually carry the gender of their last element. Moreover, the gender of abbreviations is decided by the base word{{clarify|date=January 2019}}, and shortened words act as{{clarify|date=January 2019}} the gender of the full word.{{Sfn|Donaldson|2007|pp=33\u201337}}{{Sfn|Durrell|2017|pp=12\u201316|p=}}\n\n=== English loanwords ===\nMany loanwords from English adopt the gender of their native German equivalent; the gender of other loanwords may be deduced by the word's form or ending (for example, nouns from English -''ing'' forms are neuter). Monosyllabic nouns from verbs are often masculine, and the same goes for monosyllabic words for which there is no other indication, which are mainly masculine. In many cases the gender can vary, either because of regional differences or because the noun's gender is not firmly established.{{Sfn|Donaldson|2007|pp=33\u201337}}{{Sfn|Durrell|2017|pp=12\u201316|p=}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[German articles]]\n* [[German cases]]\n* [[German nouns]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n=== Sources ===\n* {{Cite book|title=German: An Essential Grammar|last=Donaldson|first=Bruce|publisher=Routledge|year=2007|isbn=978-0-415-36602-1|location=|pages=}}\n\n* {{Cite book|title=Hammer\u2019s German Grammar and Usage|last=Durrell|first=Martin|publisher=Routledge|year=2017|isbn=978-1-138-85371-3|edition=6th|location=}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{Cite book|title=Richtig gendern|last=Diewald|first=Gabriele|last2=Steinhauer|first2=Anja|publisher=Duden|year=2017|isbn=978-3-411-74357-5|language=German}}\n* {{Cite book|title=German All-in-One For Dummies|last=Foster|first=Wendy|last2=Christensen|first2=Paulina|last3=Fox|first3=Anne|publisher=Wiley|year=2013|isbn=978-1-118-49140-9|pages=307\u2013311}}\n\n* {{Cite book|title=Die Grammatik|last=|first=|publisher=Duden|year=2016|isbn=978-3-411-04049-0|edition=9th|location=|pages=156\u2013172|language=German}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.dummies.com/languages/german/identifying-a-german-words-gender/ Identifying a German Word\u2019s Gender], ''For Dummies'' ([https://web.archive.org/web/20170824091422/http://www.dummies.com:80/languages/german/identifying-a-german-words-gender/ on the Internet Archive]).\n* [https://www.lsa.umich.edu/german/hmr/Grammatik/Gender/Gender.html Some Hints on How to Guess Gender], ''University of Michigan College of LSA'' ([https://web.archive.org/web/20180227114401/https://www.lsa.umich.edu/german/hmr/Grammatik/Gender/Gender.html on the Internet Archive]).\n[[Category:Grammatical gender]]\n[[Category:German grammar]]\n", "text_old": "{{German grammar}}\n'''Grammatical gender in German''' refers to the division of [[German nouns]] into three [[Grammatical gender|grammatical genders]]. All [[German language|German]] nouns are included in one of three genders: masculine, feminine or neuter. However the gender is not relevant to the plural forms of nouns.{{Sfn|Donaldson|2007|pp=33\u201337}}{{Sfn|Durrell|2017|pp=1\u20135}}\n\nIn German, it is useful to memorize nouns with their accompanying [[German articles#Definite article|definite article]] in order to remember their gender.<ref group=\"note\">While Donaldson (2007) says that it is imperative to do so, Durrell (2017) only mentions that is an ideal method.</ref> However, for about 80% of nouns, the grammatical gender can be deduced from their singular and plural forms{{Fix|text=does this mean the nominative forms?}} and their meaning.{{Sfn|Donaldson|2007|pp=33\u201337}}{{Sfn|Durrell|2017|pp=1\u20135}}\n\n== Noun forms ==\n[[Morphological derivation|Derivational]] suffixes in particular, together with most noun endings, consistently relate with specific genders, and there are very few frequent exceptions to this (as reflected in the first column). Nevertheless, the details in the second column are not solid rules, and their irregularities should be noted.{{Sfn|Durrell|2017|pp=1\u20135}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Noun forms and gender{{Sfn|Donaldson|2007|pp=33\u201337}}{{Sfn|Durrell|2017|pp=1\u20135}}<ref group=\"n