{"title_page": "Social Democratic Party of India", "text_new": "{{multiple issues|\n{{lead too short|date=April 2014}}\n{{recentism|date=April 2014}}\n{{unreliable sources|date=April 2014}}\n}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=September 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2015}}\n\n{{Infobox Indian political party \n|colorcode = Red\n|president = MK Faizey\n|loksabha_leader =\n|rajyasabha_leader =\n|foundation = 21 June 2009\n|headquarters = C-4, Hazrat Nizamuddin West [[New Delhi]], [[India]]-110013\n|eci = Registered-Unrecognized Party by ECI<ref name=\"ECI12032014\">{{cite web |url= http://eci.nic.in/eci_main/ElectoralLaws/OrdersNotifications/year2014/EnglishNotification_12032014.pdf |title=Names of National, State, registered-unrecognised parties and the list of free symbols|publisher= [[Election Commission of India]] |date= 12 March 2014 |accessdate=30 Oct 2016}}</ref>\n|alliance =\n|loksabha_seats =\n|rajyasabha_seats =\n|ideology=[[Social democracy]]<br />[[Anti-imperialism]]<br />[[Corruption|Anti-corruption]]<br />[[Social justice]]<br />[[Anti-fascism]]<ref>{{cite web |url= http://sdpi.in/aims-and-objectives/|title=Party aims|publisher=Social Democratic Party of India|date= 22 April 2017|accessdate=22 April 2017}}</ref>\n|publication =\n|youth =\n|students =\n|women = Women India Movement (WIM)\n|labour = SDTU (Social Democratic Trade Union)\n|peasants =\n|website = [http://sdpi.in/ Official Website]\n|party_name = '''Social Democratic Party of India'''\n|logo = [[File:SDPI Flag wite stroke.png|200px]]\n|flag = [[File:SDPI Flag.jpg|250px]]\n|colours = Green {{Colorsample|Green}} Red {{Colorsample|Red}}\n|electoral_symbol =\n}}\nThe '''Social Democratic Party of India''' is an [[India]]n [[political party]] linked to Islamist [[Popular Front Of India]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.outlookindia.com/website/story/islamist-popular-front-of-india-involved-in-terror-acts-nia-submits-report-to-go/301575}}</ref> founded on 21 June 2009.<ref name=sdpi1>{{cite news|title=On the back of a good showing, SDPI sets its sights higher|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-karnataka/on-the-back-of-a-good-showing-sdpi-sets-its-sights-higher/article4707953.ece|accessdate=17 April 2014|newspaper=The Hindu|date=12 May 2013}}</ref><ref  name=sdp2>{{cite web|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2009-09-19/pune/28080598_1_new-party-social-democratic-party-assembly-elections|title=New Party Formed|date=2009-08-11|work=The Times of India|accessdate=2010-08-11}}</ref> MK Faizey is the party's National President.<ref name=\"twocircles1\">{{cite web|url=http://twocircles.net/2014mar07/sdpi%E2%80%99s_manifesto_2014_lok_sabha_elections_released.html |title=SDPI's manifesto for 2014 Lok Sabha elections released |publisher=TwoCircles.net |date=2014-03-07 |accessdate=2014-04-17}}</ref><ref name=sdpi3>{{cite web|title=National Office Bearers|url=http://sdpi.in/portal/content/office-bearers|publisher=Official website|accessdate=3 May 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Charges and accusations ==\nKerala CPIM chief accused SDPI as an Indian version of Islamic state, after a SFI student was murdered by Campus Front of India, student wing of SDPI.<ref>{{cite web |title=SDPI is Indian version of Islamic State: Kerala CPIM chief |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/sdpi-is-indian-version-of-islamic-state-kerala-cpim-chief-1289706-2018-07-18}}</ref>\n\n===Accusation by Sunni outfits===\nSunni outfits of Kerala Samastha Kerala Jamiyyathul Ulama and Sunni Yuvajana Sangham campaigned against SDPI, accused SDPI of being extremist.<ref>{{cite web |title=Sunnis chalking out campaign against SDPI |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/kerala/sunnis-chalking-out-campaign-against-sdpi/article24514395.ece}}</ref>\n\n===Murder of CPIM, Congress, IUML workers===\nNine PFI and SDPI activists were found guilty of killing CPIM worker in 2008.<ref>{{cite web |title=Murder: 9 PFI, SDPI workers found guilty |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/kerala/murder-9-pfi-sdpi-workers-found-guilty/article26273322.ece}}</ref> \nSDPI activists were found guilty of murdering Muslim Youth League worker in Kozhikode.<ref>{{cite web |title=Two SDPI men found guilty in Youth League activist's murder|url=https://english.manoramaonline.com/districts/kozhikode/2018/11/28/two-sdpi-men-found-guilty-in-youth-league-activist-murder.html}}</ref>\nSDPI members were arrested for murder of Congress worker in Chavakkad.<ref>{{cite web |title=Noushad murdered by SDPI: Chennithala |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/kerala/noushad-murdered-by-sdpi-chennithala/article28788088.ece}}</ref> \nSeveral SDPI offices have been raided by [[Kerala Police]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-kerala/raid-at-pfi-sdpi-offices/article515027.ece|title=Raid at PFI, SDPI offices|last=|first=|date=25 March 2014|publisher=The Hindu|accessdate=25 March 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-kerala/raid-on-sdpi-offices/article5641670.ece|title=Raid on SDPI offices|last=|first=|date=25 March 2014|publisher=The Hindu|accessdate=25 March 2014}}</ref> Suspected weapons training camps and arms stockpiling were seized in [[Narath]], [[Kannur district]] from the offices and other centers of PFI and SDPI.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindu.com/2010/07/14/stories/2010071459810300.htm|title=Haul hints at arms stockpiling|last=|first=|date=25 March 2014|publisher=The Hindu/|accessdate=25 March 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/kerala/more-weapons-seized-from-narath/article4657098.ece|title=More weapons seized from Narath|last=|first=|date=25 March 2014|publisher=The Hindu|accessdate=25 March 2014}}</ref> Though the party denied any involvement, the charge-sheet filed by [[National Investigation Agency]] (NIA) blamed [[Popular Front of India]] (PFI) and their political outfit Social Democratic Party of India (SDPI) in conducting arms training camps across the state under the pretense of health awareness camps and yoga classes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/narath-arms-case-nia-chargesheet-hints-about-pfis-links-with-terrorist-outfits/1/317245.html|title=Narath arms case: NIA chargesheet hints at PFI's links with terrorist outfits|last=|first=|date=25 March 2014|publisher=indiatoday.intoday.in|accessdate=25 March 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailypioneer.com/nation/islamists-ran-jehadi-camps-in-kannur-cops.html|title=Islamsts Ran Jehadi Camps in Kannur: Cops|last=|first=|date=25 March 2014|publisher=Daily Pioneer|accessdate=25 March 2014}}</ref> According to the FIR, the 24 accused in the case were reportedly the members of the Popular Front of India (PFI) and the Social Democratic Party of India (SDPI).Cases were registered under sections 143, 147, 153(B), R/W 149 of IPC, section 5(1)(a) r/w 25(1)(a) of Arms Act, section 4 of Explosives Act and section 18 of Unlawful Activities (Prevention) Act of the [[Indian Penal Code]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/kochi/NIA-registers-FIR-in-Narath-arms-case/articleshow/21793106.cms|title=NIA registers FIR in Narath arms case|last=|first=|date=25 March 2014|work=The Times of India|accessdate=25 March 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.coastaldigest.com/index.php/news/53141-raid-on-pfi-camp-karnataka-police-team-in-kerala|title=Raid on PFI camp: Karnataka police team in Kerala|last=|first=|date=25 March 2014|publisher=Coastal Digest|accessdate=25 March 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deccanchronicle.com/131020/news-current-affairs/article/22-sdpi-members-chargesheeted-narath-case|title=22 SDPI members chargesheeted in Narath case|last=|first=|date=25 March 2014|publisher=deccanchronicle.com/|accessdate=25 March 2014}}</ref>\n\nFour SDPI activists were arrested for attack on two [[Communist Party of India (Marxist)]](CPI-M) members at Mangalam, [[Tirur]], on 29 January 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/states/kerala/4-SDPI-Workers-Held/2014/01/31/article2029293.ece|title=4 SDPI Workers Held|last=|first=|date=25 March 2014|publisher=NewIndianExpress|accessdate=25 March 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/kerala/4-held-for-attack-on-cpim-men-at-tirur/article5635874.ece|title=4 held for attack on CPI(M) men at Tirur|last=|first=|date=25 March 2014|publisher=TheHindu|accessdate=25 March 2014}}</ref>  SDPI accepted the responsibility after a video of this violent attack was aired by major television channels. However the party justified the attacks reasoning that it needs to safeguard its members. As per the party's District President,the attack was just an emotional reaction from its members to an attack the CPM executed against one of its members on the same morning.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/states/kerala/SDPI-Justifies-Attack-on-CPM-Members/2014/02/02/article2033272.ece|title=SDPI Justifies Attack on CPM Members|last=|first=|date=25 March 2014|publisher=NewIndianExpress|accessdate=25 March 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Controversy ==\nIn 2014 a private school in south Kerala removed ''[[Vande Mataram]]'' from their Independence Day programme after workers of the SDPI threatened to disrupt the programme, saying that some of the words in the song were against the religious beliefs of the Muslim community. The school also dropped the ''namaste'' gesture from a dance number performed during Independence Day celebrations, inviting sharp criticism from various quarters. The song was dropped after several rounds of rehearsals. When the issue snowballed into a raging controversy, school management denied any external pressure. SDPI justified the changes in the programme saying that they approached the school management after a number of parents complained that some words in ''Vande Matraam'' and the gesture ''namaste'' were against their religious beliefs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/68thindependenceday/i-day-shocker-kerala-school-drops-vande-mataram-from-dance-programme/article1-1252438.aspx|title=Kerala school says no to Vande Mataram in dance programme|last=|first=|date=15 August 2014|publisher=Hindustan Times|accessdate=16 August 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Activities==\n\n===Reservation in private school===\nIn line with the mandate of the Right to Education, the SDPI sought 25% of seats in private schools in the district of Tirunelveli, Tamil Nadu for the academic year 2015. The petition to the district collector also asked for transparency in school admissions and fee structure.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/ensure-25-pc-seats-to-poor-students-in-private-schools/article7124832.ece|title=Ensure 25 p.c. seats to poor students in private schools|author=Special Correspondent|work=The Hindu}}</ref>\n\n===Protest against police===\nIn April 2015, the SDPI protested against the police encounter of the 20 workers from Tamil Nadu working in the state of Andhra Pradesh. The party accused the AP police of staging a fake encounter in the name of self-defence. The party demanded the government to lodge a criminal case against the police personnel responsible for these killings.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/sdpi-protests-ap-killings/article7087775.ece|title=SDPI protests A.P. killings|author=Staff Reporter|work=The Hindu}}</ref>\n\n===Demand for road===\nIn February 2016, around 30 cadres attempted to stage \u2018sleeping protest\u2019 in front of the Divisional Office of Department of Highways, protesting to repair of the Palayamkottai \u2013 Papanasam Road (in [[Tamil Nadu]]).  Other political parties and the public had been repeatedly appealing to the Department of Highways to have this 52-km stretch re-laid. The officials had chosen to ignore the plea and were keen on re-laying only stretches that was used by ministers and other VIPs during the governor's visit to Manonmaniam Sundaranar University.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/sdpi-cadres-arrested-released/article8231601.ece |title=SDPI cadres arrested, released |publisher=The Hindu |date=2016-02-13 |accessdate=2016-12-01}}</ref>\n\n=== Women's rights ===\nThe [[Jisha Murder Case]] in 2016 created statewide agitation for a speedier justice.\n\nThe SDPI had blocked the Kerala CM{{clarify|date=September 2017}} [[Oommen Chandy]] who had come to Perumbavur to meet the kin of Jisha's. Post-visit, the CM said that the investigations are being carried out with efficiency.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.manoramaonline.com/news/just-in/kochi-dalit-woman-rape-murder-suspect-probe-perumbavoor-cm-oommen-chandy.html|title=Kerala woman's rape-murder: more details emerge, CM stopped by protesters|website=ManoramaOnline|access-date=2016-05-10}}</ref>\n\n=== Preservation of religious sentiments ===\nIn March 2016, the ''[[Mathrubhumi]]'' reproduced an offensive comment about [[Muhammad]] that was initially posted on Facebook.\n\nThe paper was forced to offer an apology after the party and other organisations outlined how the post had \"hurt the sentiments of the community\", with strong protest outside the newspaper's office.<ref>{{Cite news | url = http://www.huffingtonpost.in/2016/03/10/malayalam-daily-mathrubhu_n_9424504.html | title = Mathrubhumi Forced To Apologise For Offensive Remarks On Prophet Mohammad | newspaper = The Huffington Post | date = 2016-03-10 | access-date = 2016-05-26}}</ref>\n\n==On false accusations==\nIn 2015, the acquitted SDPI candidate, Dr. Anas, accused the NIA and the police of falsely targeting both the SDPI and the Popular Front of India. Anas had won the block panchayat election while in prison for the palm chopping case. The victory \"reflected public sentiments against police action\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nyoooz.com/kochi/96798/former-pfi-district-head-among-those-acquitted#|title=Former PFI district head among those acquitted|work=NYOOOZ}}</ref>\n\n== Regional presence ==\nSDPI has representations in 16 states of India including [[Kerala]], [[Tamil Nadu]], [[Karnataka]], [[Andrapradesh]], [[Goa]], [[Maharashtra]], [[Puducherry]], [[Madhya Pradesh]], [[Uttar Pradesh]], [[Jharkhand]], [[West Bengal]], [[Bihar]], [[Delhi]], [[Rajasthan]], [[Haryana]] and [[Manipur]]. It has made state level and district level local committees in most of the states.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://visionmp.com/sdpi-names-interim-committee-for-mp254114710784/|title=Local Committee formed|last=|first=|date=13 October 2009|publisher=Visionmp.com|accessdate=11 August 2010}}</ref>{{Failed verification|date=April 2014}} SDPI has shown its presence in recent elections 68 SDPI Candidate Won BBMP election held in [[Karnataka]], [[Kerala]], [[Rajasthan]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://coastaldigest.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=5119:sdpi-candidate-won-bbmp-election-held-in-bangalore-on-28th-mar-2010&catid=57:news-stories&Itemid=68 |title=SDPI Candidate Won BBMP election |publisher=Coastaldigest.com |date=2010-04-07 |accessdate=2014-04-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.coastaldigest.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=1199%3Asdpi-candidate-wins-sarpanch-election-in-rajasthan&Itemid=53 |title=sdpi candidate wins sarpanch election in rajasthan |publisher=Coastaldigest.com |date=2010-01-29 |accessdate=2014-04-17}}</ref> The party won 14 seats in four municipalities in the 2010 local body election in Kerala.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pd.cpim.org/2010/1031_pd/10312010_13.html |title=October 11, 2009 |publisher=Pd.cpim.org |date=2009-10-11 |accessdate=2014-04-17}}</ref>{{Unreliable source?|date=April 2014}}{{Better source|date=April 2014}} It won 62 seats in the Local body election 2011 in Tamil Nadu.<ref>It secured more than 24000 votes in Jangipur parliamentary election in bengal.It has opened account in Goa by winning 1 seat. http://sdpi.in/portal/story/good-show-sdpi-tamilnadu-local-body-elections</ref>{{Self-published source|date=April 2014}} Karnataka saw more than one lakh votes polled in favor of the party in the 24 Assembly segment but the party's individual candidates did not win any seat. He pointed out forming local alliance with the [[Bahujan Samaj Party]] to underline his party's secular credentials. However, by nominating only two non-Muslim candidates in the 24 constituencies (both in reserved constituencies), the SDPI reaffirmed its image as a party in pursuit of the Muslim vote. The SDPI State president also claimed that as the national level, the party shares a good rapport with the [[Janata Dal (United)]] as well as the Ram Vilas Paswan's [[Lok Janshakti Party]].<ref>{{cite news|author=Sudipto Mondal |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-karnataka/on-the-back-of-a-good-showing-sdpi-sets-its-sights-higher/article4707953.ece |title=On the back of a good showing, SDPI sets its sights higher |publisher=The Hindu |date=2013-05-12 |accessdate=2014-04-17}}</ref>\n\n== Presence in Indian general election, 2014 ==\nThe SDPI fielded 30 candidates in six states. The party's 2014 Election Manifesto contained several issues concerning domestic and foreign policies. The basic needs of the people, democratic rights, eradication of corruption, SCs/STs, Minorities etc. A new national water policy, implementation of Ranganath Mishra Commission and Sachar Committee reports, 100% literacy by 2020, eradication of corruption. All international treaties related to India is to be ratified by the Parliament & the Nehruvian period status should be reinstated as the leader of the Non-alignment movement. The manifesto also included the need for 10% reservation to Muslims with the inclusion of Muslim and Christian dalits in the SC category with the sub-plan for minorities and reservation for women of SC, ST, OBC and minorities in the Lok Sabha. [[Unlawful Activities (Prevention) Act]] and AFSPA would be repealed, and the enactment of Communal Violence (Prevention) Bill would be at the top priority of the party.<ref name=\"twocircles1\"/> The bill was heavily criticized by human rights groups and lawyers.<ref>{{cite news|title=State pogroms glossed over|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/state-pogroms-glossed-over/articleshow/1353464.cms|accessdate=17 April 2014|newspaper=The Times of India|date=31 Dec 2005}}</ref>\nDespite being a young party, it is poised to influence the Muslim votes for years to come. The criticism and demands raised by the party in the electioneering campaign seem sensible.<ref name=\"thehindu1\">{{cite news|author=Abdul Latheef Naha |url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/kerala/muslim-votes-not-a-monolithic-bloc/article5829659.ece |title=Muslim votes not a monolithic bloc |publisher=The Hindu |date=2014-03-25 |accessdate=2014-04-17}}</ref> In the state of Kerala, the party, with the candidates in Ponnani and Malappuram, offered to lead an alternative to Left-Right politics that the state has seen for decades.<ref name=\"thehindu1\"/> In the state of Karnataka, the Social Democratic Party of India is being supported by the [[Janata Dal (Secular)]] in Dakshin Kannada. The JD-S has extended its support \"on the principles and ideologies laid by the party at the time of its (SDPI's) birth\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.daijiworld.com/news/news_disp.asp?n_id=227618 |title=Mangalore: JD(S) backing SDPI, fighting elections on principles - M B Sadashiva |publisher=Daijiworld.com |date= |accessdate=2014-04-17}}</ref>{{Unreliable source?|date=April 2014}} The party had put a decent show in the Karnataka Local Body elections in 2013 by winning 17 seats.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://muslimmirror.com/eng/sdpi-wins-17-seats-in-karnataka-local-body-elections/ |title=SDPI wins 17 seats in Karnataka Local Body Elections |work=Muslim Mirror |date=2013-03-12 |accessdate=2014-04-17 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140416192908/http://muslimmirror.com/eng/sdpi-wins-17-seats-in-karnataka-local-body-elections/ |archive-date=2014-04-16}}</ref>{{Unreliable source?|date=April 2014}} Among the various parties who contested for the [[2014 Indian general election]] in [[Kerala]], SDPI had the highest number of candidates with criminal charges. Fourteen out of the party's 20 candidates faced criminal charges.7 out of 17 candidates from the BJP, 6 out of 9 from the CPI(M), 6 out of 15 from the Congress, all four candidates of CPI, and 3 out of the 20 candidates from the BSP had criminal cases against them.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/kerala/74-with-criminal-cases-46-crorepatis-in-the-fray-in-kerala/article5870537.ece |title=74 with criminal cases, 46 crorepatis in the fray in Kerala |work=The Hindu |date=2014-04-04 |accessdate=2014-04-18}}</ref>\nIn the recent election held in Karnataka State for Punchayath, SDPI contested in 375 seats and won 74 seats and secured 2nd position in 97 places. Thus it has gradually strengthening its political base in Karnataka state.\n\n== Presence in Tamil Nadu Legislative Assembly election, 2016 ==\nSocial Democratic Party of India (SDPI) contested 30 seats in the May 16 Assembly polls with the slogan 'driving out selfish politics and protecting public welfare politics' in the 'Gas Cylinder' symbol.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uniindia.com/sdpi-to-go-it-alone-to-contest-30-seats-in-tn-assembly-polls/election/news/451712.html |title=SDPI to go it alone, to contest 30 seats in TN Assembly polls |publisher=UniIndia.com |date=2016-04-18 |accessdate=2016-12-01}}</ref>\n\n== Presence in Karnataka Legislative Assembly election, 2013 ==\nSocial Democratic Party of India (SDPI) contested 24 seats in the May 2013 Assembly polls, 7 were contesting from Dakshina Kannada district and it is followed by Bangalore where its 5 candidates were contesting. Its state president Abdul Majeed is fighting the three-time legislator and former minister Tanveer Sait in Narashimaraja assembly segment, a constituency dominated by Muslim minorities.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/mysuru/New-party-SDPI-may-spring-surprise-in-assembly-elections/articleshow/19712784.cms|title=New party SDPI may spring surprise in assembly elections - Times of India|website=IndiaTimes.com|access-date=18 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Presence in Kerala Legislative Assembly election, 2016 ==\nThe general election for the fourteenth legislative assembly was held on May 16, 2016, to elect representatives of the 140 constituencies in [[Kerala]]. The party fielded candidates in 89 constituencies independently.<ref>{{Cite news | url = http://www.indiancrux.info/2016/02/2016-kerala-assembly-constituency-wise-election-results.html | title =2016 Kerala Legislative Assembly Election Results Constituency Wise | newspaper = Indian Crux | date = 2016-02-27 | access-date = 2016-05-26}}</ref>\n\n== Presence in Karnataka Legislative Assembly election, 2018 ==\nSocial Democratic Party of India has declared Abdul Majid K H as its candidate from Narasimharaja constituency in 2018 for [[Karnataka Legislative Assembly]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-karnataka/it-could-well-be-a-triangular-contest-in-narasimharaja-constituency/article4652695.ece |title=It could well be a triangular contest in Narasimharaja constituency |publisher=The Hindu|date=25 April 2013}}</ref> Social Democratic Party of India has decided to concentrate on Gulbarga Uttar, Chickpet in Bengaluru and Narasimharaja in Mysuru, said Mohammed Riyaz alias Riyaz Farangipet, SDPI's State secretary.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Mangalore/sdpi-decision-to-withdraw-candidate-may-help-ramanath-rai-in-bantwal/article23674989.ece |title=SDPI decision to withdraw candidate may help Ramanath Rai in Bantwal |date=26 April 2018 |website=[[The Hindu]]}}</ref> Social Democratic Party of India 's decision was taken to prevent the division of Muslim votes thereby affecting prospects of secular forces which could aid alleged communal forces, party office-bearers said.\n\n== Presence in Indian general election, 2019 ==\nThe Social Democratic Party of India, (SDPI), contested in a few selected seats in six states . Kerala, Karnataka, Tamil Nadu, Andhra Pradesh, West Bengal and Delhi in the ensuing 2019 Lok Sabha elections. In total the party will contest 15 Lok Sabha seats. While in Andhra Pradesh apart from one Lok Sabha it will field 2 candidates in the Assembly elections which are being held simultaneously.<ref>{{Cite news | url = http://https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/not-a-good-omen-for-congress-sdpi-appeal-seats-grow-in-karnataka-local-body-polls/articleshow/65678976.cms?from=mdr}}</ref>.\n\n\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n{{SIMI}}\n\n[[Category:Islamic political parties in India]]\n[[Category:Registered unrecognised political parties in India]]\n[[Category:2009 establishments in India]]\n[[Category:Social democratic parties in India]]\n", "text_old": "{{multiple issues|\n{{lead too short|date=April 2014}}\n{{recentism|date=April 2014}}\n{{unreliable sources|date=April 2014}}\n}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=September 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2015}}\n\n{{Infobox Indian political party \n|colorcode = Red\n|president = MK Faizey\n|loksabha_leader =\n|rajyasabha_leader =\n|foundation = 21 June 2009\n|headquarters = C-4, Hazrat Nizamuddin West [[New Delhi]], [[India]]-110013\n|eci = Registered-Unrecognized Party by ECI<ref name=\"ECI12032014\">{{cite web |url= http://eci.nic.in/eci_main/ElectoralLaws/OrdersNotifications/year2014/EnglishNotification_12032014.pdf |title=Names of National, State, registered-unrecognised parties and the list of free symbols|publisher= [[Election Commission of India]] |date= 12 March 2014 |accessdate=30 Oct 2016}}</ref>\n|alliance =\n|loksabha_seats =\n|rajyasabha_seats =\n|ideology=[[Social democracy]]<br />[[Anti-imperialism]]<br />[[Corruption|Anti-corruption]]<br />[[Social justice]]<br />[[Anti-fascism]]<ref>{{cite web |url= http://sdpi.in/aims-and-objectives/|title=Party aims|publisher=Social Democratic Party of India|date= 22 April 2017|accessdate=22 April 2017}}</ref>\n|publication =\n|youth =\n|students =\n|women = Women India Movement (WIM)\n|labour = SDTU (Social Democratic Trade Union)\n|peasants =\n|website = [http://sdpi.in/ Official Website]\n|party_name = '''Social Democratic Party of India'''\n|logo = [[File:SDPI Flag wite stroke.png|200px]]\n|flag = [[File:SDPI Flag.jpg|250px]]\n|colours = Green {{Colorsample|Green}} Red {{Colorsample|Red}}\n|electoral_symbol =\n}}\nThe '''Social Democratic Party of India''' is an [[India]]n [[political party]] linked to Islamist [[Popular Front Of India]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.outlookindia.com/website/story/islamist-popular-front-of-india-involved-in-terror-acts-nia-submits-report-to-go/301575}}</ref> founded on 21 June 2009.<ref name=sdpi1>{{cite news|title=On the back of a good showing, SDPI sets its sights higher|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-karnataka/on-the-back-of-a-good-showing-sdpi-sets-its-sights-higher/article4707953.ece|accessdate=17 April 2014|newspaper=The Hindu|date=12 May 2013}}</ref><ref  name=sdp2>{{cite web|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2009-09-19/pune/28080598_1_new-party-social-democratic-party-assembly-elections|title=New Party Formed|date=2009-08-11|work=The Times of India|accessdate=2010-08-11}}</ref> MK Faizey is the party's National President.<ref name=\"twocircles1\">{{cite web|url=http://twocircles.net/2014mar07/sdpi%E2%80%99s_manifesto_2014_lok_sabha_elections_released.html |title=SDPI's manifesto for 2014 Lok Sabha elections released |publisher=TwoCircles.net |date=2014-03-07 |accessdate=2014-04-17}}</ref><ref name=sdpi3>{{cite web|title=National Office Bearers|url=http://sdpi.in/portal/content/office-bearers|publisher=Official website|accessdate=3 May 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Charges and accusations ==\nKerala CPIM chief accused SDPI as an Indian version of Islamic state, after a SFI student was murdered by Campus Front of India, student wing of SDPI.<ref>{{cite web |title=SDPI is Indian version of Islamic State: Kerala CPIM chief |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/sdpi-is-indian-version-of-islamic-state-kerala-cpim-chief-1289706-2018-07-18}}</ref>\n\n===Accusation by Sunni outfits===\nSunni outfits of Kerala Samastha Kerala Jamiyyathul Ulama and Sunni Yuvajana Sangham campaigned against SDPI, accused SDPI of being extremist.<ref>{{cite web |title=Sunnis chalking out campaign against SDPI |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/kerala/sunnis-chalking-out-campaign-against-sdpi/article24514395.ece}}</ref>\n\n===Murder of CPIM, Congress, IUML workers===\nNine PFI and SDPI activists were found guilty of killing CPIM worker in 2008.<ref>{{cite web |title=Murder: 9 PFI, SDPI workers found guilty |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/kerala/murder-9-pfi-sdpi-workers-found-guilty/article26273322.ece}}</ref> \nSDPI activists were found guilty of murdering Muslim Youth League worker in Kozhikode.<ref>{{cite web |title=Two SDPI men found guilty in Youth League activist's murder|url=https://english.manoramaonline.com/districts/kozhikode/2018/11/28/two-sdpi-men-found-guilty-in-youth-league-activist-murder.html}}</ref>\nSDPI members were arrested for murder of Congress worker in Chavakkad.<ref>{{cite web |title=Noushad murdered by SDPI: Chennithala |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/kerala/noushad-murdered-by-sdpi-chennithala/article28788088.ece}}</ref> \nSeveral SDPI offices have been raided by [[Kerala Police]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-kerala/raid-at-pfi-sdpi-offices/article515027.ece|title=Raid at PFI, SDPI offices|last=|first=|date=25 March 2014|publisher=The Hindu|accessdate=25 March 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-kerala/raid-on-sdpi-offices/article5641670.ece|title=Raid on SDPI offices|last=|first=|date=25 March 2014|publisher=The Hindu|accessdate=25 March 2014}}</ref> Suspected weapons training camps and arms stockpiling were seized in [[Narath]], [[Kannur district]] from the offices and other centers of PFI and SDPI.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindu.com/2010/07/14/stories/2010071459810300.htm|title=Haul hints at arms stockpiling|last=|first=|date=25 March 2014|publisher=The Hindu/|accessdate=25 March 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/kerala/more-weapons-seized-from-narath/article4657098.ece|title=More weapons seized from Narath|last=|first=|date=25 March 2014|publisher=The Hindu|accessdate=25 March 2014}}</ref> Though the party denied any involvement, the charge-sheet filed by [[National Investigation Agency]] (NIA) blamed [[Popular Front of India]] (PFI) and their political outfit Social Democratic Party of India (SDPI) in conducting arms training camps across the state under the pretense of health awareness camps and yoga classes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/narath-arms-case-nia-chargesheet-hints-about-pfis-links-with-terrorist-outfits/1/317245.html|title=Narath arms case: NIA chargesheet hints at PFI's links with terrorist outfits|last=|first=|date=25 March 2014|publisher=indiatoday.intoday.in|accessdate=25 March 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailypioneer.com/nation/islamists-ran-jehadi-camps-in-kannur-cops.html|title=Islamsts Ran Jehadi Camps in Kannur: Cops|last=|first=|date=25 March 2014|publisher=Daily Pioneer|accessdate=25 March 2014}}</ref> According to the FIR, the 24 accused in the case were reportedly the members of the Popular Front of India (PFI) and the Social Democratic Party of India (SDPI).Cases were registered under sections 143, 147, 153(B), R/W 149 of IPC, section 5(1)(a) r/w 25(1)(a) of Arms Act, section 4 of Explosives Act and section 18 of Unlawful Activities (Prevention) Act of the [[Indian Penal Code]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/kochi/NIA-registers-FIR-in-Narath-arms-case/articleshow/21793106.cms|title=NIA registers FIR in Narath arms case|last=|first=|date=25 March 2014|work=The Times of India|accessdate=25 March 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.coastaldigest.com/index.php/news/53141-raid-on-pfi-camp-karnataka-police-team-in-kerala|title=Raid on PFI camp: Karnataka police team in Kerala|last=|first=|date=25 March 2014|publisher=Coastal Digest|accessdate=25 March 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deccanchronicle.com/131020/news-current-affairs/article/22-sdpi-members-chargesheeted-narath-case|title=22 SDPI members chargesheeted in Narath case|last=|first=|date=25 March 2014|publisher=deccanchronicle.com/|accessdate=25 March 2014}}</ref>\n\nFour SDPI activists were arrested for attack on two [[Communist Party of India (Marxist)]](CPI-M) members at Mangalam, [[Tirur]], on 29 January 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/states/kerala/4-SDPI-Workers-Held/2014/01/31/article2029293.ece|title=4 SDPI Workers Held|last=|first=|date=25 March 2014|publisher=NewIndianExpress|accessdate=25 March 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/kerala/4-held-for-attack-on-cpim-men-at-tirur/article5635874.ece|title=4 held for attack on CPI(M) men at Tirur|last=|first=|date=25 March 2014|publisher=TheHindu|accessdate=25 March 2014}}</ref>  SDPI accepted the responsibility after a video of this violent attack was aired by major television channels. However the party justified the attacks reasoning that it needs to safeguard its members. As per the party's District President,the attack was just an emotional reaction from its members to an attack the CPM executed against one of its members on the same morning.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/states/kerala/SDPI-Justifies-Attack-on-CPM-Members/2014/02/02/article2033272.ece|title=SDPI Justifies Attack on CPM Members|last=|first=|date=25 March 2014|publisher=NewIndianExpress|accessdate=25 March 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Controversy ==\nIn 2014 a private school in south Kerala removed ''[[Vande Mataram]]'' from their Independence Day programme after workers of the SDPI threatened to disrupt the programme, saying that some of the words in the song were against the religious beliefs of the Muslim community. The school also dropped the ''namaste'' gesture from a dance number performed during Independence Day celebrations, inviting sharp criticism from various quarters. The song was dropped after several rounds of rehearsals. When the issue snowballed into a raging controversy, school management denied any external pressure. SDPI justified the changes in the programme saying that they approached the school management after a number of parents complained that some words in ''Vande Matraam'' and the gesture ''namaste'' were against their religious beliefs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/68thindependenceday/i-day-shocker-kerala-school-drops-vande-mataram-from-dance-programme/article1-1252438.aspx|title=Kerala school says no to Vande Mataram in dance programme|last=|first=|date=15 August 2014|publisher=Hindustan Times|accessdate=16 August 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Activities==\n\n===Reservation in private school===\nIn line with the mandate of the Right to Education, the SDPI sought 25% of seats in private schools in the district of Tirunelveli, Tamil Nadu for the academic year 2015. The petition to the district collector also asked for transparency in school admissions and fee structure.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/ensure-25-pc-seats-to-poor-students-in-private-schools/article7124832.ece|title=Ensure 25 p.c. seats to poor students in private schools|author=Special Correspondent|work=The Hindu}}</ref>\n\n===Protest against police===\nIn April 2015, the SDPI protested against the police encounter of the 20 workers from Tamil Nadu working in the state of Andhra Pradesh. The party accused the AP police of staging a fake encounter in the name of self-defence. The party demanded the government to lodge a criminal case against the police personnel responsible for these killings.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/sdpi-protests-ap-killings/article7087775.ece|title=SDPI protests A.P. killings|author=Staff Reporter|work=The Hindu}}</ref>\n\n===Demand for road===\nIn February 2016, around 30 cadres attempted to stage \u2018sleeping protest\u2019 in front of the Divisional Office of Department of Highways, protesting to repair of the Palayamkottai \u2013 Papanasam Road (in [[Tamil Nadu]]).  Other political parties and the public had been repeatedly appealing to the Department of Highways to have this 52-km stretch re-laid. The officials had chosen to ignore the plea and were keen on re-laying only stretches that was used by ministers and other VIPs during the governor's visit to Manonmaniam Sundaranar University.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/sdpi-cadres-arrested-released/article8231601.ece |title=SDPI cadres arrested, released |publisher=The Hindu |date=2016-02-13 |accessdate=2016-12-01}}</ref>\n\n=== Women's rights ===\nThe [[Jisha Murder Case]] in 2016 created statewide agitation for a speedier justice.\n\nThe SDPI had blocked the Kerala CM{{clarify|date=September 2017}} [[Oommen Chandy]] who had come to Perumbavur to meet the kin of Jisha's. Post-visit, the CM said that the investigations are being carried out with efficiency.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.manoramaonline.com/news/just-in/kochi-dalit-woman-rape-murder-suspect-probe-perumbavoor-cm-oommen-chandy.html|title=Kerala woman's rape-murder: more details emerge, CM stopped by protesters|website=ManoramaOnline|access-date=2016-05-10}}</ref>\n\n=== Preservation of religious sentiments ===\nIn March 2016, the ''[[Mathrubhumi]]'' reproduced an offensive comment about [[Muhammad]] that was initially posted on Facebook.\n\nThe paper was forced to offer an apology after the party and other organisations outlined how the post had \"hurt the sentiments of the community\", with strong protest outside the newspaper's office.<ref>{{Cite news | url = http://www.huffingtonpost.in/2016/03/10/malayalam-daily-mathrubhu_n_9424504.html | title = Mathrubhumi Forced To Apologise For Offensive Remarks On Prophet Mohammad | newspaper = The Huffington Post | date = 2016-03-10 | access-date = 2016-05-26}}</ref>\n\n==On false accusations==\nIn 2015, the acquitted SDPI candidate, Dr. Anas, accused the NIA and the police of falsely targeting both the SDPI and the Popular Front of India. Anas had won the block panchayat election while in prison for the palm chopping case. The victory \"reflected public sentiments against police action\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nyoooz.com/kochi/96798/former-pfi-district-head-among-those-acquitted#|title=Former PFI district head among those acquitted|work=NYOOOZ}}</ref>\n\n== Regional presence ==\nSDPI has representations in 16 states of India including [[Kerala]], [[Tamil Nadu]], [[Karnataka]], [[Andrapradesh]], [[Goa]], [[Maharashtra]], [[Puducherry]], [[Madhya Pradesh]], [[Uttar Pradesh]], [[Jharkhand]], [[West Bengal]], [[Bihar]], [[Delhi]], [[Rajasthan]], [[Haryana]] and [[Manipur]]. It has made state level and district level local committees in most of the states.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://visionmp.com/sdpi-names-interim-committee-for-mp254114710784/|title=Local Committee formed|last=|first=|date=13 October 2009|publisher=Visionmp.com|accessdate=11 August 2010}}</ref>{{Failed verification|date=April 2014}} SDPI has shown its presence in recent elections 68 SDPI Candidate Won BBMP election held in [[Karnataka]], [[Kerala]], [[Rajasthan]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://coastaldigest.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=5119:sdpi-candidate-won-bbmp-election-held-in-bangalore-on-28th-mar-2010&catid=57:news-stories&Itemid=68 |title=SDPI Candidate Won BBMP election |publisher=Coastaldigest.com |date=2010-04-07 |accessdate=2014-04-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.coastaldigest.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=1199%3Asdpi-candidate-wins-sarpanch-election-in-rajasthan&Itemid=53 |title=sdpi candidate wins sarpanch election in rajasthan |publisher=Coastaldigest.com |date=2010-01-29 |accessdate=2014-04-17}}</ref> The party won 14 seats in four municipalities in the 2010 local body election in Kerala.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pd.cpim.org/2010/1031_pd/10312010_13.html |title=October 11, 2009 |publisher=Pd.cpim.org |date=2009-10-11 |accessdate=2014-04-17}}</ref>{{Unreliable source?|date=April 2014}}{{Better source|date=April 2014}} It won 62 seats in the Local body election 2011 in Tamil Nadu.<ref>It secured more than 24000 votes in Jangipur parliamentary election in bengal.It has opened account in Goa by winning 1 seat. http://sdpi.in/portal/story/good-show-sdpi-tamilnadu-local-body-elections</ref>{{Self-published source|date=April 2014}} Karnataka saw more than one lakh votes polled in favor of the party in the 24 Assembly segment but the party's individual candidates did not win any seat. He pointed out forming local alliance with the [[Bahujan Samaj Party]] to underline his party's secular credentials. However, by nominating only two non-Muslim candidates in the 24 constituencies (both in reserved constituencies), the SDPI reaffirmed its image as a party in pursuit of the Muslim vote. The SDPI State president also claimed that as the national level, the party shares a good rapport with the [[Janata Dal (United)]] as well as the Ram Vilas Paswan's [[Lok Janshakti Party]].<ref>{{cite news|author=Sudipto Mondal |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-karnataka/on-the-back-of-a-good-showing-sdpi-sets-its-sights-higher/article4707953.ece |title=On the back of a good showing, SDPI sets its sights higher |publisher=The Hindu |date=2013-05-12 |accessdate=2014-04-17}}</ref>\n\n== Presence in Indian general election, 2014 ==\nThe SDPI fielded 30 candidates in six states. The party's 2014 Election Manifesto contained several issues concerning domestic and foreign policies. The basic needs of the people, democratic rights, eradication of corruption, SCs/STs, Minorities etc. A new national water policy, implementation of Ranganath Mishra Commission and Sachar Committee reports, 100% literacy by 2020, eradication of corruption. All international treaties related to India is to be ratified by the Parliament & the Nehruvian period status should be reinstated as the leader of the Non-alignment movement. The manifesto also included the need for 10% reservation to Muslims with the inclusion of Muslim and Christian dalits in the SC category with the sub-plan for minorities and reservation for women of SC, ST, OBC and minorities in the Lok Sabha. [[Unlawful Activities (Prevention) Act]] and AFSPA would be repealed, and the enactment of Communal Violence (Prevention) Bill would be at the top priority of the party.<ref name=\"twocircles1\"/> The bill was heavily criticized by human rights groups and lawyers.<ref>{{cite news|title=State pogroms glossed over|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/state-pogroms-glossed-over/articleshow/1353464.cms|accessdate=17 April 2014|newspaper=The Times of India|date=31 Dec 2005}}</ref>\nDespite being a young party, it is poised to influence the Muslim votes for years to come. The criticism and demands raised by the party in the electioneering campaign seem sensible.<ref name=\"thehindu1\">{{cite news|author=Abdul Latheef Naha |url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/kerala/muslim-votes-not-a-monolithic-bloc/article5829659.ece |title=Muslim votes not a monolithic bloc |publisher=The Hindu |date=2014-03-25 |accessdate=2014-04-17}}</ref> In the state of Kerala, the party, with the candidates in Ponnani and Malappuram, offered to lead an alternative to Left-Right politics that the state has seen for decades.<ref name=\"thehindu1\"/> In the state of Karnataka, the Social Democratic Party of India is being supported by the [[Janata Dal (Secular)]] in Dakshin Kannada. The JD-S has extended its support \"on the principles and ideologies laid by the party at the time of its (SDPI's) birth\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.daijiworld.com/news/news_disp.asp?n_id=227618 |title=Mangalore: JD(S) backing SDPI, fighting elections on principles - M B Sadashiva |publisher=Daijiworld.com |date= |accessdate=2014-04-17}}</ref>{{Unreliable source?|date=April 2014}} The party had put a decent show in the Karnataka Local Body elections in 2013 by winning 17 seats.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://muslimmirror.com/eng/sdpi-wins-17-seats-in-karnataka-local-body-elections/ |title=SDPI wins 17 seats in Karnataka Local Body Elections |work=Muslim Mirror |date=2013-03-12 |accessdate=2014-04-17 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140416192908/http://muslimmirror.com/eng/sdpi-wins-17-seats-in-karnataka-local-body-elections/ |archive-date=2014-04-16}}</ref>{{Unreliable source?|date=April 2014}} Among the various parties who contested for the [[2014 Indian general election]] in [[Kerala]], SDPI had the highest number of candidates with criminal charges. Fourteen out of the party's 20 candidates faced criminal charges.7 out of 17 candidates from the BJP, 6 out of 9 from the CPI(M), 6 out of 15 from the Congress, all four candidates of CPI, and 3 out of the 20 candidates from the BSP had criminal cases against them.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/kerala/74-with-criminal-cases-46-crorepatis-in-the-fray-in-kerala/article5870537.ece |title=74 with criminal cases, 46 crorepatis in the fray in Kerala |work=The Hindu |date=2014-04-04 |accessdate=2014-04-18}}</ref>\nIn the recent election held in Karnataka State for Punchayath, SDPI contested in 375 seats and won 74 seats and secured 2nd position in 97 places. Thus it has gradually strengthening its political base in Karnataka state.\n\n== Presence in Tamil Nadu Legislative Assembly election, 2016 ==\nSocial Democratic Party of India (SDPI) contested 30 seats in the May 16 Assembly polls with the slogan 'driving out selfish politics and protecting public welfare politics' in the 'Gas Cylinder' symbol.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uniindia.com/sdpi-to-go-it-alone-to-contest-30-seats-in-tn-assembly-polls/election/news/451712.html |title=SDPI to go it alone, to contest 30 seats in TN Assembly polls |publisher=UniIndia.com |date=2016-04-18 |accessdate=2016-12-01}}</ref>\n\n== Presence in Karnataka Legislative Assembly election, 2013 ==\nSocial Democratic Party of India (SDPI) contested 24 seats in the May 2013 Assembly polls, 7 were contesting from Dakshina Kannada district and it is followed by Bangalore where its 5 candidates were contesting. Its state president Abdul Majeed is fighting the three-time legislator and former minister Tanveer Sait in Narashimaraja assembly segment, a constituency dominated by Muslim minorities.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/mysuru/New-party-SDPI-may-spring-surprise-in-assembly-elections/articleshow/19712784.cms|title=New party SDPI may spring surprise in assembly elections - Times of India|website=IndiaTimes.com|access-date=18 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Presence in Kerala Legislative Assembly election, 2016 ==\nThe general election for the fourteenth legislative assembly was held on May 16, 2016, to elect representatives of the 140 constituencies in [[Kerala]]. The party fielded candidates in 89 constituencies independently.<ref>{{Cite news | url = http://www.indiancrux.info/2016/02/2016-kerala-assembly-constituency-wise-election-results.html | title =2016 Kerala Legislative Assembly Election Results Constituency Wise | newspaper = Indian Crux | date = 2016-02-27 | access-date = 2016-05-26}}</ref>\n\n== Presence in Karnataka Legislative Assembly election, 2018 ==\nSocial Democratic Party of India has declared Abdul Majid K H as its candidate from Narasimharaja constituency in 2018 for [[Karnataka Legislative Assembly]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-karnataka/it-could-well-be-a-triangular-contest-in-narasimharaja-constituency/article4652695.ece |title=It could well be a triangular contest in Narasimharaja constituency |publisher=The Hindu|date=25 April 2013}}</ref> Social Democratic Party of India has decided to concentrate on Gulbarga Uttar, Chickpet in Bengaluru and Narasimharaja in Mysuru, said Mohammed Riyaz alias Riyaz Farangipet, SDPI's State secretary.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Mangalore/sdpi-decision-to-withdraw-candidate-may-help-ramanath-rai-in-bantwal/article23674989.ece |title=SDPI decision to withdraw candidate may help Ramanath Rai in Bantwal |date=26 April 2018 |website=[[The Hindu]]}}</ref> Social Democratic Party of India 's decision was taken to prevent the division of Muslim votes thereby affecting prospects of secular forces which could aid alleged communal forces, party office-bearers said.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n{{SIMI}}\n\n[[Category:Islamic political parties in India]]\n[[Category:Registered unrecognised political parties in India]]\n[[Category:2009 establishments in India]]\n[[Category:Social democratic parties in India]]\n", "name_user": "Thoufiq313", "label": "safe", "comment": "Presence in 2019 General Elections.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Social_Democratic_Party_of_India"}
